{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17535375","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17535375"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T16:55:07+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T16:55:07+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15365"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15365","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15365"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.2,0.19,0.39,0.07,0.15]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8056"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"105619"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8056","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8056"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15365"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"88048"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"16"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"4948"},{"type":"tags","id":"4981"},{"type":"tags","id":"5326"},{"type":"tags","id":"5392"},{"type":"tags","id":"5394"},{"type":"tags","id":"7786"},{"type":"tags","id":"11623"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"19561"},{"type":"contributions","id":"38490"},{"type":"contributions","id":"45761"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"105619","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/105619"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA case-control study investigates the association between coffee consumption and insomnia. The researchers define \u0027regular coffee drinker\u0027 as consuming more than three cups of coffee per day. Among 180 patients with insomnia, 120 were regular coffee drinkers. Among 220 control patients without insomnia, 80 were regular coffee drinkers.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the odds ratio for the association between regular coffee consumption and insomnia?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["2.0","2.8","3.5","4.2","5.0"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003ETo calculate the odds ratio, we first arrange the data in a two by two table:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cdiv class=\u0022table-container\u0022\u003E\u003Ctable border=\u00221\u0022\u003E\u003Ctr\u003E\u003Cth\u003E\u003C/th\u003E\u003Cth\u003EInsomnia (cases)\u003C/th\u003E\u003Cth\u003ENo insomnia (controls)\u003C/th\u003E\u003C/tr\u003E\u003Ctr\u003E\u003Ctd\u003ERegular coffee drinker\u003C/td\u003E\u003Ctd\u003Ea = 120\u003C/td\u003E\u003Ctd\u003Eb = 80\u003C/td\u003E\u003C/tr\u003E\u003Ctr\u003E\u003Ctd\u003ENot regular coffee drinker\u003C/td\u003E\u003Ctd\u003Ec = 60\u003C/td\u003E\u003Ctd\u003Ed = 140\u003C/td\u003E\u003C/tr\u003E\u003C/table\u003E\u003C/div\u003E\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe odds ratio formula is: OR = (a \u00d7 d) / (b \u00d7 c)\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESubstituting the values: OR = (120 \u00d7 140) / (80 \u00d7 60) = 16,800 / 4,800 = \u003Cstrong\u003E3.5\u003C/strong\u003E\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThis odds ratio of 3.5 indicates that the odds of being a regular coffee drinker are 3.5 times higher among people with insomnia compared to those without insomnia.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E2.0\u003C/strong\u003E - This might be mistaken for a relative risk calculation, but relative risk cannot be directly calculated from case-control studies\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E2.8\u003C/strong\u003E - This is an incorrect calculation that doesn\u0027t follow the proper odds ratio formula\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E4.2\u003C/strong\u003E - This overestimates the association and results from calculation error\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E5.0\u003C/strong\u003E - This is also an overestimate resulting from incorrect calculation\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAn odds ratio greater than 1 suggests a positive association between regular coffee consumption and insomnia. In case-control studies, we can only calculate odds ratios because participants are selected based on their outcome status (with or without insomnia) rather than their exposure status.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Odds ratio is calculated using the formula OR = (a \u00d7 d) / (b \u00d7 c) where a, b, c, and d represent the cells in a two by two table.","An odds ratio greater than 1 suggests a positive association between the exposure and outcome.","Case-control studies can only provide odds ratios, not relative risks, as sampling is based on outcome status."],"references":["Cook A, Sheikh A. Descriptive statistics (Part 2): Interpreting study results. Prim Care Respir J. 2000 Mar;8(1):16\u20137."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"88048"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15365"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"88048","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/88048"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-06-11T06:36:13+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-06-11T06:37:30+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8056"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"105619"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"16","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/16"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udcca","name":"Biostatistics","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0